  "local_port": 39572,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I uninstall Modified apk by Lucky Patcher (I can only deactivate it)?",
  "response": "Uninstalling Lucky Patcher, especially if it has been used to modify APKs or has gained elevated permissions, can sometimes be challenging. Below are comprehensive steps to help you fully remove Lucky Patcher from your Android device. Please proceed carefully and ensure you back up any important data before making significant changes to your device.\n\n### **1. Revoke Device Administrator Permissions**\n\nLucky Patcher may have been granted device administrator rights, which can prevent it from being easily uninstalled. To revoke these permissions:\n\n1. **Open Settings:**\n   - Navigate to your device's **Settings** app.\n\n2. **Access Security Settings:**\n   - Go to **Security** (this might be under **Biometrics and Security** or a similar section depending on your device).\n\n3. **Find Device Administrators:**\n   - Tap on **Device Administrators** or **Device Admin Apps**.\n\n4. **Disable Lucky Patcher:**\n   - Locate **Lucky Patcher** in the list.\n   - Uncheck the box next to it or tap **Deactivate**.\n   - Confirm the action if prompted.\n\n### **2. Uninstall Lucky Patcher via App Settings**\n\nAfter revoking administrator rights, you should be able to uninstall the app normally:\n\n1. **Open Settings:**\n   - Go back to the **Settings** app.\n\n2. **Access Apps:**\n   - Navigate to **Apps** or **Applications** > **Manage Apps**.\n\n3. **Locate Lucky Patcher:**\n   - Scroll through the list to find **Lucky Patcher**.\n\n4. **Uninstall the App:**\n   - Tap on **Lucky Patcher**.\n   - Select **Uninstall** and confirm the action.\n\n### **3. Use Android Debug Bridge (ADB) to Uninstall**\n\nIf the standard uninstallation method doesn't work, you can use ADB, a command-line tool, to remove Lucky Patcher. Here's how:\n\n#### **a. Set Up ADB on Your Computer**\n\n1. **Download ADB:**\n   - Download the **Android SDK Platform Tools** from the [official website](https://developer.android.com/studio/releases/platform-tools).\n\n2. **Extract the Files:**\n   - Unzip the downloaded file to a convenient location on your computer.\n\n#### **b. Enable Developer Options and USB Debugging on Your Android Device**\n\n1. **Enable Developer Options:**\n   - Go to **Settings** > **About Phone**.\n   - Tap on **Build Number** seven times until you see a message that developer mode is enabled.\n\n2. **Enable USB Debugging:**\n   - Go back to **Settings** > **System** > **Developer Options** (path may vary).\n   - Toggle **USB Debugging** to **On**.\n\n#### **c. Connect and Uninstall Using ADB**\n\n1. **Connect Your Device:**\n   - Use a USB cable to connect your Android device to your computer.\n   - If prompted on your device, authorize the computer for USB debugging.\n\n2. **Open Command Prompt/Terminal:**\n   - Navigate to the folder where you extracted ADB.\n   - On Windows, you can Shift + Right-click in the folder and select **Open PowerShell window here** or **Open Command window here**.\n   - On Mac/Linux, open Terminal and navigate to the ADB directory.\n\n3. **Verify Connection:**\n   ```bash\n   adb devices\n   ```\n   - You should see your device listed. If not, troubleshoot your USB connection and drivers.\n\n4. **Identify Lucky Patcher's Package Name:**\n   - Lucky Patcher's typical package name might be `com.android.patcher` or similar. To list all installed packages:\n     ```bash\n     adb shell pm list packages | grep patcher\n     ```\n     - Note the exact package name.\n\n5. **Uninstall the App:**\n   ```bash\n   adb shell pm uninstall --user 0 com.android.patcher\n   ```\n   - Replace `com.android.patcher` with the exact package name you identified.\n\n6. **Confirm Uninstallation:**\n   - After executing the command, you should see a confirmation message.\n\n### **4. Remove Lucky Patcher Using a Root File Explorer (Requires Root Access)**\n\nIf your device is rooted, you can manually delete Lucky Patcher's files:\n\n1. **Install a Root File Explorer:**\n   - Apps like **Root Explorer**, **ES File Explorer (with root permissions)**, or **Solid Explorer** can be used.\n\n2. **Grant Root Permissions:**\n   - Open the file explorer and grant it root access when prompted.\n\n3. **Navigate to the App Directory:**\n   - Go to `/system/app/` or `/system/priv-app/`.\n\n4. **Find and Delete Lucky Patcher:**\n   - Locate the folder corresponding to Lucky Patcher (e.g., `LuckyPatcher`) and delete it.\n\n5. **Reboot Your Device:**\n   - Restart your phone to apply changes.\n\n### **5. Perform a Factory Reset (Last Resort)**\n\nIf all else fails and you cannot remove Lucky Patcher through any of the above methods, performing a factory reset will remove all apps and data, restoring your device to its original state. **Warning:** This will erase all data on your device. Ensure you back up important information before proceeding.\n\n1. **Back Up Your Data:**\n   - Use Google Backup, a PC, or another backup method to save your data.\n\n2. **Open Settings:**\n   - Navigate to **Settings** > **System** > **Reset Options**.\n\n3. **Initiate Factory Reset:**\n   - Select **Erase all data (factory reset)**.\n   - Confirm and follow the on-screen instructions.\n\n4. **Set Up Your Device:**\n   - After the reset, set up your device as new. Avoid restoring from backups that might reintroduce Lucky Patcher.\n\n### **Additional Tips**\n\n- **Secure Your Device:** After removing Lucky Patcher, consider scanning your device for other potential issues using reputable antivirus software.\n  \n- **Avoid Installing Third-Party App Modifiers:** To prevent similar issues in the future, avoid installing apps from untrusted sources that require elevated permissions.\n\n- **Keep Your Device Updated:** Regularly update your Android OS to benefit from the latest security patches.\n\nIf you encounter any specific issues during these steps or need further assistance, feel free to provide more details!",
